	abstract = {An understanding of eating behaviors is an important element of health education and treatment in clinical populations. To understand the biopsychosocial profile of eating behaviors in an ecologically valid way, ecological momentary assessment ({EMA}) is appropriate because its use is able to overcome the recall bias in patient-reported outcomes ({PROs}). As appetite is a key {PRO} associated with eating behaviors, this study was done to develop an {EMA} scale to evaluate the within-individual variation of momentary appetite and uses this scale to discuss the relationships between appetite and various psychological factors.},
